            <h2 class="font-display text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 tracking-tight mb-6 pb-2 border-b border-slate-100">
              How to Choose the Right AI Note-Taking App
            </h2>
            <p class="text-sm sm:text-base text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
              When evaluating AI note-taking applications, look beyond the marketing slogans and focus on these five core technical criteria:
            </p>

            <div class="space-y-6 text-sm text-slate-600">
              <div class="p-5 rounded-2xl bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200">
                <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-sm mb-1">1. Data Ownership and Export Formats</h4>
                <p class="text-xs leading-relaxed text-slate-500">
                  Many cloud-based note apps use proprietary databases that make it difficult to export your data. If you decide to change apps later, you could lose your formatting and links. Look for platforms that support standard export formats like Markdown (like Obsidian) to ensure long-term data portability.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="p-5 rounded-2xl bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200">
                <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-sm mb-1">2. Cloud vs. Local Storage</h4>
                <p class="text-xs leading-relaxed text-slate-500">
                  Cloud storage (Notion, Mem, Evernote) offers simple cross-device syncing and collaboration, but leaves your data on external servers. Local storage (Obsidian) keeps your files on your device, providing better security and offline access.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="p-5 rounded-2xl bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200">
                <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-sm mb-1">3. Offline Availability</h4>
                <p class="text-xs leading-relaxed text-slate-500">
                  Most cloud-based AI tools require an active internet connection to communicate with language models. If you travel frequently or work offline, local-first tools like Obsidian (configured with offline LLMs) are the only way to maintain access.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="p-5 rounded-2xl bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200">
                <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-sm mb-1">4. Context Window Size</h4>
                <p class="text-xs leading-relaxed text-slate-500">
                  The context window determines how much information the AI can process at once. NotebookLM leads with a massive context window of 500,000 words per source document, making it the best option for analyzing long research files and books.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="p-5 rounded-2xl bg-slate-50 border border-slate-200">
                <h4 class="font-bold text-slate-900 text-sm mb-1">5. Platform Integration</h4>
                <p class="text-xs leading-relaxed text-slate-500">
                  Ensure the app integrates with your existing workflow. OneNote is ideal for Microsoft Office users, Notion is best for databases, and Evernote excels at OCR scanning and PDF archiving.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </section>

